title.narrative: WASH SUPPLY

description.narrative: Communities have improved access to basic drinking water and sanitation, including in schools and health facilities, particularly in target countries., which contributes to Safe And Equitable Water, Sanitation And Hygiene Services And Practices, Water, Sanitation And Hygiene Systems And Empowerment Of Communities. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Harnessing Power Of Business And Markets, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022, more Pacific children and their families, particularly the most vulnerable, are accessing adequate, equitable, affordable drinking water, sanitation and hygiene.

title.narrative: Communities have improved access to basic drinking water and sanitation, including in schools and health facilities, particularlyin target countries.

description.narrative: UNICEF helped improve WASH in schools (WinS) in 471 schools across the Pacific. Progress was also made in improving WASH in health care facilities (WinHCF), with facilities upgraded in Vanuatu (17), Kiribati (15) and Tuvalu (4). Twenty-nine facilities have been selected for support in Solomon Islands and 24 health care facilities in the Federated States of Micronesia (FSM) have been assessed. In Solomon Islands, UNICEF supported community-led total sanitation (CLTS) implementation across two provinces. Plans are underway for scaling up WASH improvements in communities, schools and health care facilities. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:02/02/2022
